
#Reset Demystified by
<p>One of the topics that I didn't cover in depth in the Pro Git book is the resetcommand. Most of the reason for this, honestly, is that I never strongly understood the command beyond the handful of specific use cases that I needed it for. I knew what the command did, but not really how it was designed to work.</p>
<p>Since then I have become more comfortable with the command, largely thanks to <a href="http://blog.plover.com/prog/git-reset.html">Mark Dominus's article</a> re-phrasing the content of the man-page, which I always found very difficult to follow. After reading that explanation of the command, I now personally feel more comfortable using reset and enjoy trying to help others feel the same way.</p>
<p>This post assumes some basic understanding of how Git branching works. If you don't really know what HEAD and the Index are on a basic level, you might want to read chapters 2 and 3 of this book before reading this post.</p>
<p><strong>The Three Trees of Git</strong></p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/trees.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>The way I now like to think about reset and checkout is through the mental frame of Git being a content manager of three different trees. By 'tree' here I really mean &quot;collection of files&quot;, not specifically the data structure. (Some Git developers will get a bit mad at me here, because there are a few cases where the Index doesn't exactly act like a tree, but for our purposes it is easier - forgive me).</p>
<p>Git as a system manages and manipulates three trees in its normal operation. Each of these is covered in the book, but let's review them.</p>
<table><tr><td><p><strong>Tree Roles</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>The HEAD</strong></p></td><td><p>last commit snapshot, next parent</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>The Index</strong></p></td><td><p>proposed next commit snapshot</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>The Working Directory</strong></p></td><td><p>sandbox</p></td></tr></table>
<p>The HEAD last commit snapshot, next parent</p>
<p>The HEAD in Git is the pointer to the current branch reference, which is in turn a pointer to the last commit you made or the last commit that was checked out into your working directory. That also means it will be the parent of the next commit you do. It's generally simplest to think of it as <strong>HEAD is the snapshot of your last commit</strong>.</p>
<p>In fact, it's pretty easy to see what the snapshot of your HEAD looks like. Here is an example of getting the actual directory listing and SHA checksums for each file in the HEAD snapshot:</p>
<p>$ cat .git/HEAD </p>
<p>ref: refs/heads/master</p>
<p>$ cat .git/refs/heads/master </p>
<p>e9a570524b63d2a2b3a7c3325acf5b89bbeb131e</p>
<p>$ git cat-file -p e9a570524b63d2a2b3a7c3325acf5b89bbeb131e</p>
<p>tree cfda3bf379e4f8dba8717dee55aab78aef7f4daf</p>
<p>author Scott Chacon  1301511835 -0700</p>
<p>committer Scott Chacon  1301511835 -0700</p>
<p>initial commit</p>
<p>$ git ls-tree -r cfda3bf379e4f8dba8717dee55aab78aef7f4daf</p>
<p>100644 blob a906cb2a4a904a152...   README</p>
<p>100644 blob 8f94139338f9404f2...   Rakefile</p>
<p>040000 tree 99f1a6d12cb4b6f19...   lib</p>
<p>The Index next proposed commit snapshot</p>
<p>The Index is your proposed next commit. Git populates it with a list of all the file contents that were last checked out into your working directory and what they looked like when they were originally checked out. It's not technically a tree structure, it's a flattened manifest, but for our purposes it's close enough. When you run git commit, that command only looks at your Index by default, not at anything in your working directory. So, it's simplest to think of it as <strong>the Index is the snapshot of your next commit</strong>.</p>
<p>$ git ls-files -s</p>
<p>100644 a906cb2a4a904a152e80877d4088654daad0c859 0  README</p>
<p>100644 8f94139338f9404f26296befa88755fc2598c289 0  Rakefile</p>
<p>100644 47c6340d6459e05787f644c2447d2595f5d3a54b 0    lib/simplegit.rb</p>
<p>The Working Directory sandbox, scratch area</p>
<p>Finally, you have your working directory. This is where the content of files are placed into actual files on your filesystem so they're easily edited by you. <strong>The Working Directory is your scratch space, used to easily modify file content.</strong></p>
<p>$ tree</p>
<p>.</p>
<p>├── README</p>
<p>├── Rakefile</p>
<p>└── lib</p>
<p>    └── simplegit.rb</p>
<p>1 directory, 3 files</p>
<p><strong>The Workflow</strong></p>
<p>So, Git is all about recording snapshots of your project in successively better states by manipulating these three trees, or collections of contents of files.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/workflow.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>Let's visualize this process. Say you go into a new directory with a single file in it. We'll call this V1 of the file and we'll indicate it in blue. Now we run git init, which will create a Git repository with a HEAD reference that points to an unborn branch (aka, <em>nothing</em>)</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/ex2.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>At this point, only the <strong>Working Directory</strong> tree has any content.</p>
<p>Now we want to commit this file, so we use git add to take content in your Working Directory and populate our Index with the updated content</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/ex3.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>Then we run git commit to take what the Index looks like now and save it as a permanent snapshot pointed to by a commit, which HEAD is then updated to point at.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/ex4.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>At this point, all three of the trees are the same. If we run git status now, we'll see no changes because they're all the same.</p>
<p>Now we want to make a change to that file and commit it. We will go through the same process. First we change the file in our working directory.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/ex5.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>If we run git status right now we'll see the file in red as &quot;changed but not updated&quot; because that entry differs between our Index and our Working Directory. Next we run git add on it to stage it into our Index.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/ex6.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>At this point if we run git status we will see the file in green under 'Changes to be Committed' because the Index and HEAD differ - that is, our proposed next commit is now different from our last commit. Those are the entries we will see as 'to be Committed'. Finally, we run git commit to finalize the commit.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/ex7.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>Now git status will give us no output because all three trees are the same.</p>
<p>Switching branches or cloning goes through a similar process. When you checkout a branch, it changes <strong>HEAD</strong> to point to the new commit, populates your<strong>Index</strong> with the snapshot of that commit, then checks out the contents of the files in your <strong>Index</strong> into your <strong>Working Directory</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>The Role of Reset</strong></p>
<p>So the reset command makes more sense when viewed in this context. It directly manipulates these three trees in a simple and predictable way. It does up to three basic operations.</p>
<p>Step 1: Moving HEAD killing me --soft ly</p>
<p>The first thing reset will do is move what HEAD points to. Unlike checkout it does not move what branch HEAD points to, it directly changes the SHA of the reference itself. This means if HEAD is pointing to the 'master' branch, runninggit reset 9e5e6a4 will first of all make 'master' point to 9e5e6a4 before it does anything else.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/reset-soft.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>No matter what form of reset with a commit you invoke, this is the first thing it will always try to do. If you add the flag --soft, this is the <strong>only</strong> thing it will do. With --soft, reset will simply stop there.</p>
<p>Now take a second to look at that diagram and realize what it did. It essentially undid the last commit you made. When you run git commit, Git will create a new commit and move the branch that HEAD points to up to it. When you reset back toHEAD~ (the parent of HEAD), you are moving the branch back to where it was without changing the Index (staging area) or Working Directory. You could now do a bit more work and commit again to accomplish basically what git commit --amend would have done.</p>
<p>Step 2: Updating the Index having --mixed feelings</p>
<p>Note that if you run git status now you'll see in green the difference between the Index and what the new HEAD is.</p>
<p>The next thing reset will do is to update the Index with the contents of whatever tree HEAD now points to so they're the same.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/reset-mixed.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>If you specify the --mixed option, reset will stop at this point. This is also the default, so if you specify no option at all, this is where the command will stop.</p>
<p>Now take another second to look at THAT diagram and realize what it did. It still undid your last commit, but also <em>unstaged</em> everything. You rolled back to before you ran all your git adds <em>AND</em> git commit.</p>
<p>Step 3: Updating the Working Directory math is --hard, let's go shopping</p>
<p>The third thing that reset will do is to then make the Working Directory look like the Index. If you use the --hard option, it will continue to this stage.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/reset-hard.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>Finally, take yet a third second to look at <em>that</em> diagram and think about what happened. You undid your last commit, all the git adds, <em>and</em> all the work you did in your working directory.</p>
<p>It's important to note at this point that this is the only way to make the resetcommand dangerous (ie: not working directory safe). Any other invocation ofreset can be pretty easily undone, the --hard option cannot, since it overwrites (without checking) any files in the Working Directory. In this particular case, we still have <strong>v3</strong> version of our file in a commit in our Git DB that we could get back by looking at our reflog, but if we had not committed it, Git still would have overwritten the file.</p>
<p>Overview</p>
<p>That is basically it. The reset command overwrites these three trees in a specific order, stopping when you tell it to.</p>
<ul><li>#1) Move whatever branch HEAD points to (stop if --soft)</li><li>#2) THEN, make the Index look like that (stop here unless --hard)</li><li>#3) THEN, make the Working Directory look like that</li></ul>
<p>There are also --merge and --keep options, but I would rather keep things simpler for now - that will be for another article.</p>
<p>Boom. You are now a reset master.</p>
<p><strong>Reset with a Path</strong></p>
<p>Well, I lied. That's not actually all. If you specify a path, reset will skip the first step and just do the other ones but limited to a specific file or set of files. This actually sort of makes sense - if the first step is to move a pointer to a different commit, you can't make it point to <em>part</em> of a commit, so it simply doesn't do that part. However, you can use reset to update part of the Index or the Working Directory with previously committed content this way.</p>
<p>So, assume we run git reset file.txt. This assumes, since you did not specify a commit SHA or branch that points to a commit SHA, and that you provided no reset option, that you are typing the shorthand for git reset --mixed HEAD file.txt, which will:</p>
<ul><li><s>#1) Move whatever branch HEAD points to (stop if --soft)</s></li><li>#2) THEN, make the Index look like that <s>(stop here unless --hard)</s></li></ul>
<p>So it essentially just takes whatever file.txt looks like in HEAD and puts that in the Index.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/reset-path1.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>So what does that do in a practical sense? Well, it <em>unstages</em> the file. If we look at the diagram for that command vs what git add does, we can see that it is simply the opposite. This is why the output of the git status command suggests that you run this to unstage a file.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/reset-path2.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>We could just as easily not let Git assume we meant &quot;pull the data from HEAD&quot; by specifying a specific commit to pull that file version from to populate our Index by running something like git reset eb43bf file.txt.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/reset-path3.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>So what does that mean? That functionally does the same thing as if we had reverted the content of the file to <strong>v1</strong>, ran git add on it, then reverted it back to<strong>v3</strong> again. If we run git commit, it will record a change that reverts that file back to<strong>v1</strong>, even though we never actually had it in our Working Directory again.</p>
<p>It's also pretty interesting to note that like git add --patch, the reset command will accept a --patch option to unstage content on a hunk-by-hunk basis. So you can selectively unstage or revert content.</p>
<p><strong>A fun example</strong></p>
<p>I may use the term &quot;fun&quot; here a bit loosely, but if this doesn't sound like fun to you, you may drink while doing it. Let's look at how to do something interesting with this newfound power - squashing commits.</p>
<p>If you have this history and you're about to push and you want to squash down the last N commits you've done into one awesome commit that makes you look really smart (vs a bunch of commits with messages like &quot;oops.&quot;, &quot;WIP&quot; and &quot;forgot this file&quot;) you can use reset to quickly and easily do that (as opposed to using git rebase -i).</p>
<p>So, let's take a slightly more complex example. Let's say you have a project where the first commit has one file, the second commit added a new file and changed the first, and the third commit changed the first file again. The second commit was a work in progress and you want to squash it down.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/squash-r1.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>You can run git reset --soft HEAD~2 to move the HEAD branch back to an older commit (the first commit you want to keep):</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/squash-r2.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>And then simply run git commit again:</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/squash-r3.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>Now you can see that your reachable history, the history you would push, now looks like you had one commit with the one file, then a second that both added the new file and modified the first to it's final state.</p>
<p><strong>Check it out</strong></p>
<p>Finally, some of you may wonder what the difference between checkout and resetis. Well, like reset, checkout manipulates the three trees and it is a bit different depending on whether you give the command a file path or not. So, let's look at both examples separately.</p>
<p>git checkout [branch]</p>
<p>Running git checkout [branch] is pretty similar to running git reset --hard [branch] in that it updates all three trees for you to look like [branch], but there are two important differences.</p>
<p>First, unlike reset --hard, checkout is working directory safe in this invocation. It will check to make sure it's not blowing away files that have changes to them. Actually, this is a subtle difference, because it will update all of the working directory except the files you've modified if it can - it will do a trivial merge between what you're checking out and what's already there. In this case, reset --hard will simply replace everything across the board without checking.</p>
<p>The second important difference is how it updates HEAD. Where reset will move the branch that HEAD points to, checkout will move HEAD itself to point to another branch.</p>
<p>For instance, if we have two branches, 'master' and 'develop' pointing at different commits, and we're currently on 'develop' (so HEAD points to it) and we run git reset master, 'develop' itself will now point to the same commit that 'master' does.</p>
<p>On the other hand, if we instead run git checkout master, 'develop' will not move, HEAD itself will. HEAD will now point to 'master'. So, in both cases we're moving HEAD to point to commit A, but <em>how</em> we do so is very different. reset will move the branch HEAD points to, checkout moves HEAD itself to point to another branch.</p>
<p><img alt="https://git-scm.com/images/reset/reset-checkout.png" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>git checkout [branch] file</p>
<p>The other way to run checkout is with a file path, which like reset, does not move HEAD. It is just like git reset [branch] file in that it updates the index with that file at that commit, but it also overwrites the file in the working directory. Think of it like git reset --hard [branch] file - it would be exactly the same thing, it is also not working directory safe and it also does not move HEAD. The only difference is that reset with a file name will not accept --hard, so you can't actually run that.</p>
<p>Also, like git reset and git add, checkout will accept a --patch option to allow you to selectively revert file contents on a hunk-by-hunk basis.</p>
<p><strong>Cheaters Gonna Cheat</strong></p>
<p>Hopefully now you understand and feel more comfortable with the resetcommand, but are probably still a little confused about how exactly it differs from checkout and could not possibly remember all the rules of the different invocations.</p>
<p>So to help you out, I've created something that I pretty much hate, which is a table. However, if you've followed the article at all, it may be a useful cheat sheet or reminder. The table shows each class of the reset and checkout commands and which of the three trees it updates.</p>
<p>Pay especial attention to the 'WD Safe?' column - if it's red, really think about it before you run that command.</p>
<table><tr><td><p><strong>head</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>index</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>work dir</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>wd safe</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Commit Level</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>reset --soft [commit]</strong></p></td><td><p>REF</p></td><td><p>NO</p></td><td><p>NO</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>reset [commit]</strong></p></td><td><p>REF</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td><td><p>NO</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>reset --hard [commit]</strong></p></td><td><p>REF</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td><td><p>NO</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>checkout [commit]</strong></p></td><td><p>HEAD</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>File Level</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>reset (commit) [file]</strong></p></td><td><p>NO</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td><td><p>NO</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>checkout (commit) [file]</strong></p></td><td><p>NO</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td><td><p>YES</p></td><td><p>NO</p></td></tr></table>
